Due to the steady increase in life expectancy, the number of patients over 80 
years of age proposed for coronary angioplasty is increasing significantly. The 
elderly patient is a patient at high cardiovascular risk and high risk of 
bleeding; whose severity of prognosis depends of comorbidities. The radial 
approach presents particularities and technical difficulties that have to be 
known in this part of the population, but reduce vascular and hemorrhagic 
complications, as well as mortality. Because of greater safety, the radial 
approach is therefore the first choice for the elderly.

